4. Seeding¶

In [5]:
def seed_everything(seed=42):
    random.seed(seed)
    os.environ['PYTHONHASHSEED'] = str(seed)
    np.random.seed(seed)
    torch.manual_seed(seed)
    torch.cuda.manual_seed(seed)
    torch.backends.cudnn.deterministic = True
seed_everything()

frequent_words =[]
for line in tweet_text:
  for w in line.split():
    if word_freq[w] > 3: # exclude all words which occur less than 3 times from the vocabulary
      frequent_words.append(w)
In [13]:
# create wor_to_index vocabulary with indexes for UNK and PAD
'''
* UNK - unknown token - is used to replace the rare words that did not fit in our vocabulary.
* PAD - our device processes the training data in batches and all the sequences in our batch 
        should have the same length. The max length of our tweets are 16, any tweets that are less 
        than that in word length will be padded from either side to match max length. 
'''
vocab_set = set(frequent_words)
word_to_index = {word: i for i, word in enumerate(vocab_set, 2)} # the first two indexes are reserved for <pad> and <unk>
word_to_index['<pad>'] = 1 
word_to_index['<unk>'] = 0

word_to_index

6.3. Twitter Dataset class¶

In [15]:
# codes adapted from https://www.kaggle.com/code/xv7d111/modern-models-techniques-with-real-project-i/notebook#3.2--Frequency-of-the-Most-Common-Words-for-Every-Class
class Twitter_Dataset(data.Dataset):
    def __init__(self, data, word_to_index):
        self.word_to_index = word_to_index 

        # sort tweets by length in order to decrease the amount of padding and make training fast
        data['length'] = data['tweets'].apply(lambda x: len(x.split()))
        data.sort_values(by='length', inplace=True)

        self.label = data['labels'].values
        self.tweet = data['tweets'].apply(lambda x: x.split()).values

    def __len__(self):
        return len(self.label)

    def __getitem__(self, item):
        sequence = [self.word_to_index[w] for w in self.tweet[item] if w in self.word_to_index]
        target = self.label[item]

        return {'target': target, 'sequence': sequence}

train_data = Twitter_Dataset(train_set, word_to_index)
val_data = Twitter_Dataset(val_set, word_to_index)
test_data = Twitter_Dataset(test_set, word_to_index)

As suggested by the Pytorch documentation, we implement dataset class (torch.utils.data.Dataset) which provides training, validation and test examples via it's get_item method to the torch.utils.data.DataLoader. torch.utils.data.DataLoader has a collate_fn parameter which is used to transform a list of samples into a batch. collate_fn, pads the input text, truncating it to some predefined length.

6.4. Padding function¶

In [17]:
def pad_text(tokenized_reviews, seq_length):
    padded_reviews = []
    for review in tokenized_reviews:
        if len(review) == seq_length:
            padded_reviews.append(review)
        else:
            padded_reviews.append(review + (seq_length - len(review)) * [1]) # index for <pad> is marked 1 in our vocabulary
    return padded_reviews

6.5. Collate function¶

In [18]:
def collate_fn(batch):
    target = [b['target'] for b in batch]
    sequence = [b['sequence'] for b in batch]
    max_length = max([len(b) for b in sequence])
    sequence = pad_text(sequence, max_length) # apply padding function here 
    # return tensors for labels and the text sequence
    return {'target': torch.tensor(target, device=device, dtype=torch.long),
            'sequence': torch.tensor(sequence, device=device, dtype=torch.long)
            }

7. Pretrained GloVe Embeddings¶

7.1. Load Pre-Trained Embeddings¶

Every line in Glove.txt file contains the word and embedding vector pair. The file contains a lot of lines since the embeddings were trained on millions of words. We will only extract words that is in our vocabulary.

In [21]:
# GloVe embeddings - code adapted from https://analyticsindiamag.com/hands-on-guide-to-word-embeddings-using-glove/
glove_emb = {}

with open(dir_path+'/GloVe/glove.twitter.27B.200d.txt', 'r') as f:
    for line in f.readlines():
        vector = line.split() 
        word = vector[0] # word
        dims = vector[1:] # vector 200d
        if word in word_to_index.keys(): 
            glove_emb[word] = np.array(dims) # assign word to its vector embedding in glove_emb dictionary

missing_words = len(word_to_index) - len(glove_emb)

print(f'GloVe embeddings found in our word_to_index vocabulary: {len(glove_emb)} | missing: {missing_words} ~ {missing_words / len(word_to_index) * 100:.1f}%')

7.2. Creating Embedding Matrix¶

In [22]:
for word in word_to_index:
    if word not in glove_emb.keys(): # if word in the word_to_index vocabulary IS NOT in glove embedding
        glove_emb[word] = np.random.uniform(-0.25, 0.25, 200)  # create arbitary 200d matrix with random numbers between -0.25 and 0.25

# create embedding matrix that will act as a look-up table
def create_embedding_matrix(word_to_index, emb, dims):
    # create np.zeros matrix with dimensions (length of our vocab + 1, 200), words that are unkown <unk> will be assigned 0
    embedding_matrix = np.zeros((len(word_to_index) + 1, dims)) 
    for word, index in word_to_index.items():
        if word in emb: # if word in the word_to_index vocabulary IS in glove embedding
            embedding_matrix[index] = emb[word] # assign word to its vector embedding in glove_emb dictionary
    return embedding_matrix

embedding_matrix = create_embedding_matrix(word_to_index, glove_emb, 200)

8. Bidirectional LSTM (BiLSTM)¶

In [23]:
from matplotlib.text import Text
class BiLSTM(nn.Module):

    def __init__(self, vocab_size, embedding_dim, hidden_size, num_layers, output_size, drop_p):
        super().__init__()

        self.vocab_size = vocab_size
        self.hidden_size = hidden_size 
        self.n_layers = num_layers
        
        self.embedding = nn.Embedding(vocab_size, embedding_dim)
        # bidirection=True and batch_first returns: [num_layers * 2, batch, hidden_size]
        self.lstm = nn.LSTM(embedding_dim, hidden_size, num_layers, bidirectional=True, batch_first=True, dropout=drop_p if num_layers > 1 else 0)
        self.Linear = nn.Linear(hidden_size * 2, hidden_size) # concatenate hidden states
        # Dropout layer for regularizing and preventing possible overfitting 
        # It randomly zeroes some of the elements of the input tensor with probability of drop_p
        self.Dropout = nn.Dropout(drop_p)
        self.output = nn.Linear(hidden_size, output_size)


    def forward(self, text):
        embedded_words = self.embedding(text) # map the words to their vectors representations
        # hidden [num_layers * num_directions, batch, hidden_size
        # cell: [seq_length * 2, batch, hidden_size]
        output, (hidden, cell) = self.lstm(embedded_words)
        hidden = torch.cat([hidden[-2, :, :], hidden[-1, :, :]], dim=1) # concatenating left and right context
        out = nn.functional.leaky_relu(self.Linear(hidden), .001) # negative_slope=0.001,
        out = self.Dropout(out) 
        
        return self.output(out)

9.Training Loop ¶

In [24]:
def train_func(model, optimizer, criterion, iterator):
    # metrics placeholder
    accuracy_list = []
    f1_list = []
    loss_list = []
    
    model.train() 
    
    for batch in iterator:
        optimizer.zero_grad()
        
        text = batch['sequence']
        label = batch['target']

        output = model(text)
                
        loss = criterion(output, label) # loss function

        ## ---- L2 regularization ----
        # lambdaParam = torch.tensor(0.001).to(device)
        # l2_reg = torch.tensor(0.).to(device)
        # for param in model.parameters():
        #     l2_reg += torch.norm(param)
        # loss += lambdaParam * l2_reg
        # NOTE: We will be using weight decay on AdamW optimizer for L2 regularization instead 

        loss.backward() # backpropogation

        # Gradient clipping for exploding gradients 
        nn.utils.clip_grad_norm_(model.parameters(), 1)  
        
        # optimizer
        optimizer.step()

        # taking max value from prediction probabilities
        output = output.argmax(1) 
        
        # detach to exclude elements of computational graph of the tensor from gradient
        # copy the tensor to cpu and convert it to numpy array.
        output = output.detach().cpu().numpy() 
        label = label.detach().cpu().numpy()

        # append loss, accuracy and f1 matrices 
        loss_list.append(loss.detach().cpu().numpy().item()) 
        accuracy_list.append(accuracy_score(label, output)) 
        f1_list.append(f1_score(label, output, average='macro'))

    # mean score values per epoch
    loss = np.mean(loss_list).round(4) 
    f1 = np.round(np.mean(f1_list) * 100, 1) 
    accuracy = np.round(np.mean(accuracy_list) * 100, 1) 

    return loss, f1, accuracy

10.Validation Loop¶

In [25]:
def eval_func(model, criterion, iterator):
    # metrics placeholder
    accuracy_list = []
    f1_list = []
    loss_list = []

    model.eval()
    
    for batch in iterator:

        text = batch['sequence']
        label = batch['target']
        
        with torch.no_grad(): # we don't calculate gradients for eval

            output = model(text)

            loss = criterion(output, label) # loss function

        # taking max value from prediction probabilities
        output = output.argmax(1) 
        
        # detach to exclude elements of computational graph of the tensor from gradient calculation
        # copy the tensor to cpu and convert it to numpy array.
        output = output.detach().cpu().numpy() 
        label = label.detach().cpu().numpy()

        # append loss, accuracy and f1 matrices 
        loss_list.append(loss.detach().cpu().numpy().item()) 
        accuracy_list.append(accuracy_score(label, output)) 
        f1_list.append(f1_score(label, output, average='macro'))

    # mean score values per epoch
    loss = np.mean(loss_list).round(4) 
    f1 = np.round(np.mean(f1_list) * 100, 1) 
    accuracy = np.round(np.mean(accuracy_list) * 100, 1)  

    return loss, f1, accuracy

11. Prediction Loop¶

In [26]:
def pred(model, iterator):

    accuracy_list = []
    f1_list = []
    loss_list = []

    model.eval() 
    
    for batch in iterator:

        text = batch['sequence']
        label = batch['target']

        with torch.no_grad(): 

            output = model(text)

            loss = criterion(output, label) 
        
        output = output.argmax(1) 
        
        output = output.detach().cpu().numpy() 
        label = label.detach().cpu().numpy()

        loss_list.append(loss.detach().cpu().numpy().item()) 
        accuracy_list.append(accuracy_score(label, output)) 
        f1_list.append(f1_score(label, output, average='macro'))

    loss = np.mean(loss_list).round(4) 
    f1 = np.round(np.mean(f1_list) * 100, 1) 
    accuracy = np.round(np.mean(accuracy_list) * 100, 1) 
    name = type(model).__name__ # the name of the Model
    return loss, f1, accuracy, name

12. Running Loop¶

In [27]:
def training_model(model, optimizer, criterion, train_iterator, eval_iterator, epochs):
    print('\nTraining Started...\n')
    # variables for early stopping
    last_best_eval_acc = 0
    train_losses = []
    val_losses = []
    train_accuracies = []
    val_accuracies = []

    ##================================TENSORBOARD=============================##
    # https://stackoverflow.com/questions/48951136/plot-multiple-graphs-in-one-plot-using-tensorboard 
    layout = {
    "ABCDE": {
        "loss": ["Multiline", ["loss/train", "loss/validation"]],
        "accuracy": ["Multiline", ["accuracy/train", "accuracy/validation"]],
        "f1": ["Multiline", ["f1/train", "f1/validation"]],
        },
    }
    ##========================================================================##
    writer = SummaryWriter()
    writer.add_custom_scalars(layout)

    for epoch in range(epochs): 
        start_t = time.time()  # start time counter

        loss, f1, acc = train_func(model, optimizer, criterion, train_iterator)  # train
        eval_loss, eval_f1, eval_acc = eval_func(model, criterion, eval_iterator)  # evaluate
        
        ##=====================TENSORBOARD======================##
        writer.add_scalar("loss/train", loss, epoch)
        writer.add_scalar("accuracy/train", acc, epoch)
        writer.add_scalar("f1/train", f1, epoch)
        writer.add_scalar("loss/validation", eval_loss, epoch)
        writer.add_scalar("accuracy/validation", eval_acc, epoch)
        writer.add_scalar("f1/validation", eval_f1, epoch)
        ##======================================================##

        # append loss and accuracy values for train and validation
        train_losses.append(loss)
        train_accuracies.append(acc)
        val_losses.append(eval_loss)
        val_accuracies.append(eval_acc)

        secs = int(time.time() - start_t)  # end time counter
        mins = secs / 60  # convert time to minutes

        # best model scores
        if eval_acc > last_best_eval_acc: # if current eval_acc is greater then the last_best_eval_acc 
            last_best_eval_acc = eval_acc # update last_best_eval_acc to be the new best evaluation accuracy
            
            best_loss = loss
            best_acc = acc
            best_f1 = f1
            
            best_eval_loss = eval_loss
            best_eval_acc = eval_acc
            best_eval_f1 = eval_f1

            best_model = model.state_dict() # best model parameters
            best_epoch = epoch + 1  # epoch starts from 0, therefore we add 1
            stop = 0 # reset stop counter if best epoch has been found
            
            # print the results for current best epoch
            print(
                f'BEST EPOCH: [{best_epoch}/{epochs} | time: {mins:.2f}/min]::: TRAIN [loss: {best_loss} | acc: {best_acc} | f1-score: {best_f1}] & EVAL [loss: {best_eval_loss} | acc: {best_eval_acc} | f1-score: {best_eval_f1}]\n')
        
        # if current eval_acc is greater then the last_best_eval_acc add 1 step to stop
        else:
            # print the current epoch results
            print(
                f'Epoch: [{epoch + 1}/{epochs} | time: {mins:.2f}/min]::: TRAIN [loss: {loss} | acc: {acc} | f1-score: {f1}] & EVAL [loss: {eval_loss} | acc: {eval_acc} | f1-score: {eval_f1}]\n')
        
        # Scheduler to decay learning rate
        scheduler.step()
        print('LR:', scheduler.get_last_lr()) # print the decayed learning rate each epoch

    writer.close() # close tensorboard

    return train_losses, val_losses, train_accuracies, val_accuracies

# code adapted from https://stackoverflow.com/questions/49201236/check-the-total-number-of-parameters-in-a-pytorch-model#:~:text=To%20get%20the%20parameter%20count,name%20and%20the%20parameter%20itself.
from prettytable import PrettyTable
def count_parameters(model):
    table = PrettyTable(["Modules", "Parameters"])
    total_params = 0
    for name, parameter in model.named_parameters():
        if not parameter.requires_grad: continue
        params = parameter.numel()
        table.add_row([name, params])
        total_params+=params
    print(table)
    return print(f"{type(model).__name__} model with no pre-trained embedding has {total_params} total trainable parameters")

# code adapted from https://stackoverflow.com/questions/49201236/check-the-total-number-of-parameters-in-a-pytorch-model#:~:text=To%20get%20the%20parameter%20count,name%20and%20the%20parameter%20itself.
from prettytable import PrettyTable
def count_parameters(model):
    table = PrettyTable(["Modules", "Parameters"])
    total_params = 0
    for name, parameter in model.named_parameters():
        if not parameter.requires_grad: continue
        params = parameter.numel()
        table.add_row([name, params])
        total_params+=params
    print(table)
    return print(f"{type(model).__name__} model with tuned pre-trained embedding has {total_params} total trainable parameters")

def pred_generator(model, iterator,):

    model.eval() 
    preds = []
    targets = []
    for batch in iterator:

        text = batch['sequence']
        label = batch['target']

        # FEED DATA
        with torch.no_grad(): 

            output = model(text)
        
        output = output.argmax(1) 
        
        output = output.detach().cpu().numpy() 
        label = label.detach().cpu().numpy()

        preds.append(output)
        targets.append(label)

    # stack the predictions 
    predictions = np.vstack([preds])
    target_labels = np.vstack([targets])
    return predictions, target_labels

def plot_confusion_matrix(cm, classes,normalize=False,title='Confusion matrix',cmap=plt.cm.Reds):
    """
    This function prints and plots the confusion matrix.
    Normalization can be applied by setting `normalize=True`.
    """
    if normalize:
        cm = cm.astype('float') / cm.sum(axis=1)[:, np.newaxis]
        print("Normalized confusion matrix")
    else:
        print('Confusion matrix, without normalization')

    print(cm)

    plt.imshow(cm, interpolation='nearest', cmap=cmap)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.colorbar()
    tick_marks = np.arange(len(classes))
    plt.xticks(tick_marks, classes, rotation=45)
    plt.yticks(tick_marks, classes)

    fmt = '.2f' if normalize else 'd'
    thresh = cm.max() / 2.
    for i, j in itertools.product(range(cm.shape[0]), range(cm.shape[1])):
        plt.text(j, i, format(cm[i, j], fmt),
                 horizontalalignment="center",verticalalignment="top",
                 color="white" if cm[i, j] > thresh else "black")

    plt.ylabel('True label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.savefig('hyperas-confusion-matrix.png')

def call_precision_recall_curve(truelabel,predictedlabel,actualprediction,label):
    
    #print(truelabel.shape)
    #print(actualprediction.shape)
    
    precision, recall, _ = precision_recall_curve(truelabel,actualprediction)
    au = auc(recall, precision)
    print("Area under graph "+str(au))
    print("-------------------------------------------------")
    rec_score = recall_score(truelabel,predictedlabel,pos_label=1,average='binary')
    precise_score = precision_score(truelabel,predictedlabel,pos_label=1,average='binary')
    f1 = f1_score(truelabel,predictedlabel,pos_label=1, average='binary')
    print("Precision for positive review "+str(precise_score))
    print("Recall for positive review "+str(rec_score))
    print("F1-score for positive review  " + str(f1))
    print("-------------------------------------------------")
    rec_score = recall_score(truelabel,predictedlabel,pos_label=0,average='binary')
    precise_score = precision_score(truelabel,predictedlabel,pos_label=0,average='binary')
    f1 = f1_score(truelabel,predictedlabel,pos_label=0, average='binary')
    print("Precision for negative review "+str(precise_score))
    print("Recall for negative review "+str(rec_score))
    print("F1-score for negative review  " + str(f1))
    
    
    #plot the no-skill line too
    positive_cases = sum(truelabel)/len(truelabel)
    plt.plot([0, 1], [positive_cases, positive_cases], linestyle='--')
    
    
    
    # In matplotlib < 1.5, plt.fill_between does not have a 'step' argument
    step_kwargs = ({'step': 'post'}
                   if 'step' in signature(plt.fill_between).parameters
                   else {})
    plt.step(recall, precision, color='b', alpha=0.2,
             where='post')
    plt.fill_between(recall, precision, alpha=0.2, color='b', **step_kwargs)

    plt.xlabel('Recall')
    plt.ylabel('Precision')
    plt.ylim([0.0, 1.05])
    plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
    plt.title('Precision-Recall Curve')
    plt.savefig('Precision-Recall-Curve-hyperas')

def training_model_gridsearch(model, optimizer, criterion, train_iterator, eval_iterator, epochs):
    stop = 0  
    last_best_eval_acc = 0
    start_t_run = time.time()
    for epoch in range(epochs): # Epochs Loop 
        
        start_t = time.time()  # start training time

        loss, f1, acc = train_func(model, optimizer, criterion, train_iterator)  # train model
        eval_loss, eval_f1, eval_acc = eval_func(model, criterion, eval_iterator)  # evaluate model

        secs = int(time.time() - start_t)  # time after training finished
        mins = secs / 60  # time in minutes
        
        # best model scores
        if eval_acc > last_best_eval_acc: # if current  eval_acc is greater then the last_best_eval_acc 
            last_best_eval_acc = eval_acc # update last_best_eval_acc to be the new best evaluation accuracy
            
            best_loss = loss
            best_acc = acc
            best_f1 = f1
            
            best_eval_loss = eval_loss
            best_eval_acc = eval_acc
            best_eval_f1 = eval_f1

            best_epoch = epoch + 1 

            print(f' >> Best Epoch: [{best_epoch}/{epochs} | time: {mins:.2f}/min]::: TRAIN [loss: {best_loss} | acc: {best_acc} | f1-score: {best_f1}] & EVAL [loss: {best_eval_loss} | acc: {best_eval_acc} | f1-score: {best_eval_f1}]')
    
        # if current eval_acc is greater then the last_best_eval_acc add 1 step to stop
        else:
            stop += 1
            print(
                f' >> Epoch: [{epoch + 1}/{epochs} | time: {mins:.2f}/min]::: TRAIN [loss: {loss} | acc: {acc} | f1-score: {f1}] & EVAL [loss: {eval_loss} | acc: {eval_acc} | f1-score: {eval_f1}]')
        
        # Early Stopping when stop counter reaches 5 with no improvement on accuracies
        if stop == 5:
            
            
            break     
    return best_epoch, best_loss, best_acc, best_f1, best_eval_loss, best_eval_acc, best_eval_f1

# code adapted from https://github.com/paudelprabesh/Hyperparameter-Tuning-In-LSTM-Network/blob/main/notebooks/grid-search/grid_search-final.ipynb
best_params = []

def fit_lstm_grid():
  min_val_acc = 0
  vocab_size = len(word_to_index)
  embedding_dim = 200
  output_size = 2
  n_layers = 2
  dropout=0.5
  gamma=0.1
  batch_size=32
  num_epochs=10


  for learning_rate, hidden_size, lambda_norm in hyper_para_grid:
    print(f'LEARNING RATE: {learning_rate}, HIDDEN SIZE: {hidden_size}, LAMBDA_NORM: {lambda_norm}')
    BiLSTM_model_gs = BiLSTM(vocab_size,embedding_dim,hidden_size,n_layers,output_size,dropout)
    BiLSTM_model_gs = BiLSTM_model_gs.to(device) 

    criterion = nn.CrossEntropyLoss().to(device)
    optimizer = optim.AdamW(BiLSTM_model_gs.parameters(), lr=learning_rate, weight_decay=lambda_norm*(np.sqrt(batch_size/(len(train_loader)*num_epochs))))
    scheduler = torch.optim.lr_scheduler.StepLR(optimizer, step_size=1, gamma=gamma) 
    BiLSTM_model_gs.embedding.weight = nn.Parameter(torch.tensor(embedding_matrix, dtype=torch.float32))
    BiLSTM_model_gs.embedding.weight.requires_grad = False
    BiLSTM_model_gs = BiLSTM_model_gs.to(device) 

    best_epoch, best_loss, best_acc, best_f1, best_eval_loss, best_eval_acc, best_eval_f1 = \
    training_model_gridsearch(BiLSTM_model_gs, optimizer, criterion, train_loader, val_loader, epochs=num_epochs)
    
    if best_eval_acc > min_val_acc:
      min_val_acc = best_eval_acc
      best_params = [learning_rate, hidden_size, lambda_norm]
      print('------ Best Parameter Combinations ------', best_params)
    
  return best_params

def pred_generator(model, iterator,):

    model.eval() 
    preds = []
    targets = []
    for batch in iterator:

        text = batch['sequence']
        label = batch['target']

        # FEED DATA
        with torch.no_grad(): 

            output = model(text)
        
        output = output.argmax(1) 
        
        output = output.detach().cpu().numpy() 
        label = label.detach().cpu().numpy()

        preds.append(output)
        targets.append(label)

    # stack the predictions 
    predictions = np.vstack([preds])
    target_labels = np.vstack([targets])
    return predictions, target_labels

# -https://github.com/paudelprabesh/Hyperparameter-Tuning-In-LSTM-Network/blob/main/notebooks/bayesian-hyperas/imdb_hyperSeach_final.ipynb
def plot_confusion_matrix(cm, classes,normalize=False,title='Confusion matrix',cmap=plt.cm.Reds):
    """
    This function prints and plots the confusion matrix.
    Normalization can be applied by setting `normalize=True`.
    """
    if normalize:
        cm = cm.astype('float') / cm.sum(axis=1)[:, np.newaxis]
        print("Normalized confusion matrix")
    else:
        print('Confusion matrix, without normalization')

    print(cm)

    plt.imshow(cm, interpolation='nearest', cmap=cmap)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.colorbar()
    tick_marks = np.arange(len(classes))
    plt.xticks(tick_marks, classes, rotation=45)
    plt.yticks(tick_marks, classes)

    fmt = '.2f' if normalize else 'd'
    thresh = cm.max() / 2.
    for i, j in itertools.product(range(cm.shape[0]), range(cm.shape[1])):
        plt.text(j, i, format(cm[i, j], fmt),
                 horizontalalignment="center",verticalalignment="top",
                 color="white" if cm[i, j] > thresh else "black")

    plt.ylabel('True label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.savefig('hyperas-confusion-matrix.png')

def call_precision_recall_curve(truelabel,predictedlabel,actualprediction,label):
    
    #print(truelabel.shape)
    #print(actualprediction.shape)
    
    precision, recall, _ = precision_recall_curve(truelabel,actualprediction)
    au = auc(recall, precision)
    print("Area under graph "+str(au))
    print("-------------------------------------------------")
    rec_score = recall_score(truelabel,predictedlabel,pos_label=1,average='binary')
    precise_score = precision_score(truelabel,predictedlabel,pos_label=1,average='binary')
    f1 = f1_score(truelabel,predictedlabel,pos_label=1, average='binary')
    print("Precision for positive review "+str(precise_score))
    print("Recall for positive review "+str(rec_score))
    print("F1-score for positive review  " + str(f1))
    print("-------------------------------------------------")
    rec_score = recall_score(truelabel,predictedlabel,pos_label=0,average='binary')
    precise_score = precision_score(truelabel,predictedlabel,pos_label=0,average='binary')
    f1 = f1_score(truelabel,predictedlabel,pos_label=0, average='binary')
    print("Precision for negative review "+str(precise_score))
    print("Recall for negative review "+str(rec_score))
    print("F1-score for negative review  " + str(f1))
    
    
    #plot the no-skill line too
    positive_cases = sum(truelabel)/len(truelabel)
    plt.plot([0, 1], [positive_cases, positive_cases], linestyle='--')
    
    
    
    # In matplotlib < 1.5, plt.fill_between does not have a 'step' argument
    step_kwargs = ({'step': 'post'}
                   if 'step' in signature(plt.fill_between).parameters
                   else {})
    plt.step(recall, precision, color='b', alpha=0.2,
             where='post')
    plt.fill_between(recall, precision, alpha=0.2, color='b', **step_kwargs)

    plt.xlabel('Recall')
    plt.ylabel('Precision')
    plt.ylim([0.0, 1.05])
    plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
    plt.title('Precision-Recall Curve')
    plt.savefig('Precision-Recall-Curve-hyperas')
